Watch him break stuff!</span><br>  Posts: 1626<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(8/13/03 6:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=388.topic&index=13>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Posting privs on Guild Rep forum, and PoH feedback.</span><hr size=1> My issue is not if the zone stays on reservation or not, in that, as I said, if I was there and the reserving guild asked me to leave, I'd leave as that is per the rules in place. <br>
<br>
However, why would we force a plane to remain empty on a day that is reserved, when the repops replace so quickly?<br>
<br>
Example: Friday, when someone has Hate booked. If they enter the zone and find 6 people trying for their epic piece, are we going to remove the guild in question from posting rights? Or from rotation rights?<br>
<br>
 If they leave when asked, the mobs they killed will be back up within 20ish minutes, and the guild going up there, is going for those mobs... there is, at most, a 20 minute loss in time, and that's if the group there completely cleared the entire zone. <br>
<br>
Unless a raiding guild is going to use the plane for the entire 24 hours they have booked off, why should we punish, or have a punishment for, people who use it when the reserving guild is not there?<br>
<br>
In the old days of an 8 hour repop, it was because you could screw someone's entire raid. Now, when it is less than half an hour at least, probably closer to 20 minutes, where is the justification for punishment? The mobs that someone 'might have been able to kill'?<br>
<br>
Certainly, if people *have* to book a plane, desipite my skepticism that any group of 6 planable characters would not be able to single pull, and kill most of the mobs in hate, then by all means, book it, and ask anyone who is there when they arrive, to leave. <br>
<br>
The punishment aspect was originally there, I would estimate, to prevent people from taking mobs that would be denied to the group reserving the plane. <br>
<br>
Now that removing those mobs is a distinct impossibility for any length of time, why is there a moratorium on entering the zone when the reserving guild is not yet raiding? <br>
<br>
If the guild is going to raid for a full four or 10 hours, sure, but for the time they are not there, why prohibit people from using the zone? <br>
<br>
Why does the reservation for the 4/8/12 hour raid make the rest of the time a 'no fly' area, when there is no longer any harm caused by killing the mobs in hate? There is no denial of content to a guild raiding hate, if there is a group in for the 12 hours before their raid: their mobs are up and ready to go, with as much chance for drops as ever. <br>
<br>
It is akin to sebilis for respawn, difficulty, and number of groups able to function in an area. Sebilis does, in fact, have an epic encounter with in it as well, though not alagorical to this zone, admittedly. <br>
<br>
If it is, though, only epic drops that people are interested in, and that is the sole and only reason to be on a reserved calandar system despite a fast repop, might I inquire as to why Lord Begurgle, and moreover, Lake Rathe, not on a calandar'd reservations system? Lord Begurgle is much more uncommon than the minibosses in hate, even. The mobs in Permafrost drop loot as well as items for an epic quest, why is permafrost not on a calandar reservation system? <br>
<br>
I am not trying to be dismissive, or even antagonistic. I am not, at all, opposed to people reserving the zone, and if I was xp grinding and/or epic farming and a guild with a reservation said &quot;excuse me, we have a reservation...&quot; I wouldn't be upset or anything but polite. <br>
<br>
However, I do think that reserving the entire plane, for the entire 24 hours, (unless your raid is going to last for the entire 24 hours) is now too drastic a situation for the zone's mechanics. <br>
<br>
If the even minority wish is to keep hate on a reserved calandar, by all means, keep it there. <br>
<br>
However, realize that with the changes to the zone, comes the situational change that makes punishing people for 'intruding' on the 24 hour period an obsolete measure. <br>
<br>
Not leaving when asked by a reserving guild, certainly would be against the rules, and I'd support a shift in that direction gladly. But to make the entire zone inaccessable for likely 3 times as long as your raid itself will last, (6 hour raid, 18 hours inaccessable) is not exactly the intention of the caladar system. <br>
<br>
If the system is built to allow access to the most players, in a fair way, by all means, and with no hesitation from me, make it that way to the utmost:<br>
<br>
When a reserving guild enters the zone, all members they don't want in the zone are required to leave. However, until they begin their raid, allow people to group in the zone. It causes them no distress, as the mobs that they want to kill are back up, likely before they are finished pulling the zone in area. <br>
<br>
My point is that this zone is now able to be greatly shared and with no harm to those who would reserve the zone. <br>
<br>
Why not adapt the rules to cover this new situation, rather than keeping a model that, working well for the old hate, would be easily retuned for the new hate?<br>
<br>
If nothing else, sticking to rules  that were made before the revamp ignores the very basic fact that the revamp occured. The zone is very differant now, and while it may be that some guilds, on the server, need to reserve the plane to get any sort of results from going, they don't need to reserve the plane for the entire day, anymore. <br>
<br>
It does not protect the reserving guild in any way, to have mobs up for 4,6,10 hours that would respawn in 20 minutes if they were killed in that time. <br>
<br>
I would suggest the middle ground of retaining reservations but allowing people to be there before the reserving guild as long as they leave when the reserving guild enters the zone, would be a change that suits the new nature of the zone while still respecting the unique elements of the zone. <br>
<br>
Thoughts?<br>
<br>
Yers,<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
